        "content": {
          "introduction": "The most common way to form the past tense is to add the word 'ne' before a verb. It's derived from the word 'nende' which means 'formerly'.",
          "phrases": [
            {
                "dholuo": "Nende",
                "english": "Formerly",
                "notes": "Is usually contracted to 'Ne'."
              }
            ],
            "grammar_note": "Let's see how this is used in practice."
              }
        },
        {
        "type": "table",
        "title": "ðŸ“š Use of 'ne' to indicate the past.", 
        "content": {
            "introduction": "Here's how to conjugate verbs in past tense using 'ne'.",
            "columns": ["English (Present tense)", "Dholuo (Present tense)", "English (Present tense)", "Dholuo (Past Tense)", "Dhouluo (Past tense - contracted)"],
            "rows": [
                ["I am writing", "Andiko", "I wrote", "Nende andiko or Ne andiko", "Nandiko"],
                ["You are writing", "Indiko", "You wrote", "Nende indiko or ne indiko", "Nindiko"],
                ["He/She is writing", "Ondiko", "He/She wrote", "Nende ondiko or ne ondiko", "Nondiko"],
                ["We are writing", "Wandiko", "We wrote", "Ne wandiko", "Nende wandiko or ne wandiko"],
                ["You (plural) are writing", "Undiko", "You (plural) wrote", "Nende undiko or ne undiko", "Nundiko"],
                ["They are writing", "Gi ndiko", "They wrote", "Ne gindiko", "Nende gindiko or ne gindiko"]
              ],
            "grammar_note": "When a word ending in a vowel is followed by a word starting with a vowel, the first vowel is dropped. Thus 'Ne andiko' is contracted to 'nandiko'."
            }
